# Splitting data into train and test sets

test_data = data_interpolated[data_interpolated.index >= '2023-01-01']

test_size = test_data.shape[0]

In[7]:
from statsmodels.tsa.seasonal import seasonal_decompose

# Decomposing the data into trend, seasonal, and residual components using additive and multiplicative models
decomposition_additive = seasonal_decompose(monthly_data['Price'], model='additive')
decomposition_multiplicative = seasonal_decompose(monthly_data['Price'], model='multiplicative')

# Plotting the additive decomposition
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
plt.subplot(411)
plt.plot(decomposition_additive.observed, label='Observed')
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.subplot(412)
plt.plot(decomposition_additive.trend, label='Trend')
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.subplot(413)
plt.plot(decomposition_additive.seasonal, label='Seasonal')
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.subplot(414)
plt.plot(decomposition_additive.resid, label='Residual')
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Plotting the multiplicative decomposition
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
plt.subplot(411)
plt.plot(decomposition_multiplicative.observed, label='Observed')
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.subplot(412)
plt.plot(decomposition_multiplicative.trend, label='Trend')
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.subplot(413)
plt.plot(decomposition_multiplicative.seasonal, label='Seasonal')
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.subplot(414)
plt.plot(decomposition_multiplicative.resid, label='Residual')
plt.legend(loc='upper left')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
In[8]:
from statsmodels.tsa.holtwinters import ExponentialSmoothing

# Fitting a Holt-Winters model to the data and forecasting for the next year
holt_winters_model = ExponentialSmoothing(train_data['Price'], trend='add', seasonal='add', seasonal_periods=12)
holt_winters_fit = holt_winters_model.fit()
holt_winters_forecast = holt_winters_fit.forecast(steps=12)

# Plotting the Holt-Winters forecast
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.plot(train_data['Price'], label='Train Data')
plt.plot(test_data['Price'], label='Test Data', color='orange')
plt.plot(holt_winters_forecast, label='Holt-Winters Forecast', color='green')
plt.title('Holt-Winters Forecast')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Price')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

In[9]:
from statsmodels.tsa.arima.model import ARIMA
from statsmodels.tsa.statespace.sarimax import SARIMAX
import statsmodels.api as sm

# Fitting an ARIMA model to the daily data
arima_model = ARIMA(train_data['Price'], order=(5,1,0))
arima_fit = arima_model.fit()

# Diagnostic check for the ARIMA model
arima_fit.plot_diagnostics(figsize=(10, 8))
plt.show()

# Fitting a SARIMA model to the daily data to check if it fits better
sarima_model = SARIMAX(train_data['Price'], order=(5,1,0), seasonal_order=(1,1,1,12))
sarima_fit = sarima_model.fit(disp=False)

# Diagnostic check for the SARIMA model
sarima_fit.plot_diagnostics(figsize=(10, 8))
plt.show()

# Forecasting the series for the next three months using the better model
arima_forecast = arima_fit.forecast(steps=90)
sarima_forecast = sarima_fit.forecast(steps=90)

# Plotting the forecasts
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.plot(train_data['Price'], label='Train Data')
plt.plot(test_data['Price'], label='Test Data', color='orange')
plt.plot(test_data.index, arima_forecast, label='ARIMA Forecast', color='green')
plt.plot(test_data.index, sarima_forecast, label='SARIMA Forecast', color='red')
plt.title('ARIMA and SARIMA Forecast')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Price')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
